# TikZ Figure Rules

`arrows.meta` and `calc` are already loaded by `style.sty`. Add `positioning` to the document preamble for any figure with multiple nodes:

```latex
\usetikzlibrary{positioning}
```

## Absolute Rule: No Hardcoded Coordinates

```latex
% FORBIDDEN — never write positions like these:
\draw (2.3, 1.7) -- (4, 0.5);
\node at (3, 2) {text};
```

The only permitted absolute coordinate is an explicit origin anchor:
```latex
\coordinate (origin) at (0, 0);
```

Everything else must be relative to a named node or derived via `calc`.

## Required Patterns

### Node Spacing
```latex
\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=2em]
  \node[circle, draw] (v) {$v$};
  \node[circle, draw, right=3em of v] (u) {$u$};
  \node[circle, draw, below=2em of v] (w) {$w$};
\end{tikzpicture}
```

### Relative Offsets (`calc` library)
```latex
\node at ($(v)+(0, 2em)$) {label};
\coordinate (mid) at ($(A)!0.5!(B)$);            % midpoint
\coordinate (pt)  at ($(A)!0.5!(B)+(0, 1em)$);   % midpoint + offset
```

### Repeated Elements — Always Use `\foreach`
```latex
% Row of nodes (never copy-paste with different numbers):
\foreach \i in {0, 1, 2, 3} {
    \node[circle, draw, minimum size=1.5em]
        (h-\i) [right={\i * 2.5em} of origin] {$h_{\i}$};
}

% Connect consecutive nodes:
\foreach \i [remember=\i as \lasti (initially 0)] in {1, 2, 3} {
    \draw[-{Latex}] (h-\lasti) -- (h-\i);
}
```

### Arrows (`arrows.meta` already loaded)
```latex
\draw[-{Latex}] (A) -- (B);
\draw[-{Stealth[scale=1.2]}] (A) to[bend left=20] (B);
\draw[{Circle}-{Latex}] (A) -- (B);
```

## Node Naming Convention

Use names that match the math:
- `node-v`, `neighbor-u`, `graph-G` for graph elements
- `input-layer`, `hidden-1`, `hidden-2`, `output-layer` for neural networks
- `feature-x`, `message-m`, `agg-h` for GNN operations

Never use: `n1`, `n2`, `v1`, `v2`, `a`, `b`, `temp`

## Self-Check Before Finalizing

Scan the code for patterns matching `(\d+\.?\d*,\s*\d+\.?\d*)` — numeric coordinate pairs. The only allowed occurrence is `\coordinate (origin) at (0, 0)`. If any others exist, refactor them to use named-node positioning before outputting.

## File Organization

Each figure goes in its own file in `tikz-figs/`, named to match the content:

```
tikz-figs/
  gnn-message-passing.tikz
  architecture-overview.tikz
  graph-isomorphism-example.tikz
```

The `.tikz` file contains **only** the `tikzpicture` environment — no preamble, no `\begin{figure}`. Include in the document with:

```latex
\begin{figure}[t]
  \centering
  \input{tikz-figs/figure-name.tikz}
  \caption{Caption.}
  \label{fig:figure-name}
\end{figure}
```

Prefer `gnn-message-passing.tikz` over `figure1.tikz` — names should be permanent and descriptive, not positional.
